The paper deals with the problem of finding and enumerating minimum $k$-cuts in a graph, which is a fundamental problem in algorithms, combinatorics, and graph theory. The paper combines ideas from randomized contraction algorithms (cs.DS), tree packing results (cs.CG), extremal set theory (cs.DM), and computational complexity (cs.CC) to obtain a new algorithmic and extremal bound for the problem. The paper also draws connections between minimum $k$-cuts and VC-dimension, which is a concept from computational geometry (cs.CG) and machine learning (cs.LG).
